    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-07-12T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-07-12T11:00:00-05:00" n="94"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15 a 1/414a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-07-12T12:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 12, 1927—noon</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. The press in this country has several times reported from English sources
                    statements similar to that which appeared Sunday, July 10, in <hi rend="italic"
                        >New York Times</hi>, as follows:<note n="59" xml:id="d94fn59">Quoted
                        passage not paraphrased.</note>
                    <pb facs="0183" n="97" xml:id="pg_97"/>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“According to the reports received here (i. e. London) the official
                            American experts at Geneva have been strongly reinforced by unofficial
                            representatives of great concerns whose probable interests lie in the
                            direction of contracts for steel plants and other indispensable
                            concomitants of a big navy. Much of the pugnacious spirit in which
                            reports to the American press from Geneva have been conceived is
                            attributed here to the activities of these unofficial
                            propagandists.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Does statement that representatives of steel plants or manufacturing concerns are
                    in Geneva or are interfering in any way with deliberations contain any
                    truth?</p>
                <p>The <hi rend="italic">New York Times</hi> also has an editorial based on British
                    information that the United States, Great Britain, and Japan would have been
                    saved $750,000,000 through British extension of age limit alone, and that
                    reduction on the size of cruisers would have been a great saving. The first
                    statement is, of course, absurd, and second is wholly inaccurate unless total
                    tonnage is reduced; cost of building small cruisers is more proportionately than
                    to build large ones, and they cost more to maintain. These points should be
                    borne in mind in event of statements at plenary session or at any other time, in
                    your judgment, when press statements are given out.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
